reflecting the dynamic and creative culture of tenth-century England. Through an analysis of the extraordinarily sophisticated Latin in which these documents were written, this book demonstrates the literary ambitions of their draughtsmen (who may certainly be considered as Anglo-Latin literary authors in their own right), and also sheds light on the political ideologies of Anglo-Saxon England's most powerful and enigmatic kings and churchmen. Most tantalising of all, perhaps, is the fact that the language of royal charters, which may preserve some of the very words uttered by the king, provides an unparalleled view of the mechanisms by whichthe developing kingdom of England was governed. Not only does it indicate the increasingly sophisticated bureaucracy of an administratively advanced state, but it also reveals an atmosphere of literary and cultural attainment, emanating directly from the king's court, as rich as any in the early medieval Insular world. Ben Snook teaches History at the Godolphin and Latymer School, London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCharterszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aDiplomatics, LatinzEngland. 0aLawzEnglandxLanguagexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLaw, Anglo-SaxonxLanguage. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAdministrative State.  aAnglo-Saxon Charters.  aAnglo-Saxon Kings.  aBureaucracy.  aEarly Medieval Insular World.  aLand Ownership.  aLatin Language.  aPolitical Power.  aRoyal Court.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204479640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782044796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782044796/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Packag